Tracks which context-tree node ids have already been injected into a given Claude session, so the Read/Grep/Glob hook doesn't re-inject the same chain on every tool call.

State is one JSON file per session at `.context/.cache/hook-<sanitized-session-id>.json`, holding a `BTreeSet<String>` of served node ids. `state_path` sanitizes the session id to `[A-Za-z0-9._-]` (non-matching chars become `_`) before building the path — two session ids differing only in special characters will collide on the same file. `load` is deliberately fail-open: a missing file, unreadable file, or corrupt JSON all silently return an empty set rather than erroring, since the worst acceptable outcome is a redundant re-injection, never a blocked hook. `save` is the only fallible entry point, returning `CtxError::Io` (with the literal placeholder path `"<session-state>"`) if JSON encoding or the write fails.

`ENV_SESSION_ID` (`"CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID"`) is the env var the harness sets for the current session; CLI path mode reads it to share the same per-session ledger that `--hook` mode writes, so a node manually served via CLI won't be re-shown by the hook and vice versa — this cross-mode coupling depends on both paths agreeing on this constant and on `state_path`'s sanitization/location logic.

`load<E: Env>(env: &E, session: &str) -> BTreeSet<String>` and `save<E: Env>(env: &E, session: &str, served: &BTreeSet<String>) -> Result<(), CtxError>` are generic over the `Env` trait (from `crate::env`), which abstracts filesystem access — likely for test injection.